The CSS font-family Property\par
In CSS, we use the font-family property to specify the font of a text.\par
\par
Note: If the font name is more than one word, it must be in quotation marks, like: "Times New Roman".\par
\par
Tip: The font-family property should hold several font names as a "fallback" system, to ensure maximum compatibility between browsers/operating systems. Start with the font you want, and end with a generic family (to let the browser pick a similar font in the generic family, if no other fonts are available). The font names should be separated with comma. Read more about fallback fonts in the next chapter.\par
\par
Example\par
Specify some different fonts for three paragraphs:\par
\par
.p1 \{\par
  font-family: "Times New Roman", Times, serif;\par
\}\par
\par
.p2 \{\par
  font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;\par
\}\par
\par
.p3 \{\par
  font-family: "Lucida Console", "Courier New", monospace;\par
\}\par
=================================================================================\par
CSS Font Style\par
Font Style\par
The font-style property is mostly used to specify italic text.\par
\par
This property has three values:\par
\par
normal - The text is shown normally\par
italic - The text is shown in italics\par
oblique - The text is "leaning" (oblique is very similar to italic, but less supported)\par
Example\par
p.normal \{\par
  font-style: normal;\par
\}\par
\par
p.italic \{\par
  font-style: italic;\par
\}\par
\par
p.oblique \{\par
  font-style: oblique;\par
\}\par
Font Weight\par
The font-weight property specifies the weight of a font:\par
\par
Example\par
p.normal \{\par
  font-weight: normal;\par
\}\par
\par
p.thick \{\par
  font-weight: bold;\par
\}\par
Font Variant\par
The font-variant property specifies whether or not a text should be displayed in a small-caps font.\par
\par
In a small-caps font, all lowercase letters are converted to uppercase letters. However, the converted uppercase letters appears in a smaller font size than the original uppercase letters in the text.\par
\par
Example\par
p.normal \{\par
  font-variant: normal;\par
\}\par
\par
p.small \{\par
  font-variant: small-caps;\par
\}\par
===================\par
CSS Font Size\par
Font Size\par
The font-size property sets the size of the text.\par
\par
Being able to manage the text size is important in web design. However, you should not use font size adjustments to make paragraphs look like headings, or headings look like paragraphs.\par
\par
Always use the proper HTML tags, like <h1> - <h6> for headings and <p> for paragraphs.\par
\par
The font-size value can be an absolute, or relative size.\par
\par
Absolute size:\par
\par
Sets the text to a specified size\par
Does not allow a user to change the text size in all browsers (bad for accessibility reasons)\par
Absolute size is useful when the physical size of the output is known\par
Relative size:\par
\par
Sets the size relative to surrounding elements\par
Allows a user to change the text size in browsers\par
Note: If you do not specify a font size, the default size for normal text, like paragraphs, is 16px (16px=1em).\par
\par
Set Font Size With Pixels\par
Setting the text size with pixels gives you full control over the text size:\par
\par
Example\par
h1 \{\par
  font-size: 40px;\par
\}\par
\par
h2 \{\par
  font-size: 30px;\par
\}\par
\par
p \{\par
  font-size: 14px;\par
\}\par
Tip: If you use pixels, you can still use the zoom tool to resize the entire page.\par
\par
Set Font Size With Em\par
To allow users to resize the text (in the browser menu), many developers use em instead of pixels.\par
\par
1em is equal to the current font size. The default text size in browsers is 16px. So, the default size of 1em is 16px.\par
\par
The size can be calculated from pixels to em using this formula: pixels/16=em\par
\par
Example\par
h1 \{\par
  font-size: 2.5em; /* 40px/16=2.5em */\par
\}\par
\par
h2 \{\par
  font-size: 1.875em; /* 30px/16=1.875em */\par
\}\par
\par
p \{\par
  font-size: 0.875em; /* 14px/16=0.875em */\par
\}\par
In the example above, the text size in em is the same as the previous example in pixels. However, with the em size, it is possible to adjust the text size in all browsers.\par
\par
Unfortunately, there is still a problem with older versions of Internet Explorer. The text becomes larger than it should when made larger, and smaller than it should when made smaller.\par
\par
ADVERTISEMENT\par
Use a Combination of Percent and Em\par
The solution that works in all browsers, is to set a default font-size in percent for the <body> element:\par
\par
Example\par
body \{\par
  font-size: 100%;\par
\}\par
\par
h1 \{\par
  font-size: 2.5em;\par
\}\par
\par
h2 \{\par
  font-size: 1.875em;\par
\}\par
\par
p \{\par
  font-size: 0.875em;\par
\}\par
Our code now works great! It shows the same text size in all browsers, and allows all browsers to zoom or resize the text!\par
\par
Responsive Font Size\par
The text size can be set with a vw unit, which means the "viewport width".\par
\par
That way the text size will follow the size of the browser window:\par
\par
Hello World\par
Resize the browser window to see how the font size scales.\par
\par
Example\par
<h1 style="font-size:10vw">Hello World</h1>\par
\highlight1 Viewport is the browser window size. 1vw = 1% of viewport width. If the viewport is 50cm wide, 1vw is 0.5cm.\par
\par
\highlight0 CSS Font Property\par
The CSS Font Property\par
To shorten the code, it is also possible to specify all the individual font properties in one property.\par
\par
The font property is a shorthand property for:\par
\par
font-style\par
font-variant\par
font-weight\par
font-size/line-height\par
font-family\par
Note: The font-size and font-family values are required. If one of the other values is missing, their default value are used.\par
\par
Example\par
Use font to set several font properties in one declaration:\par
\par
p.a \{\par
  font: 20px Arial, sans-serif;\par
\}\par
\par
p.b \{\par
  font: italic small-caps bold 12px/30px Georgia, serif;\par
\}\par
